<br>
Mage + warrior + cleric + paladin + bard + rogue in sirens.  High uptime, medium length kills, occaisional nasty effects including one overpull+charm wipeout.  Used right click nuke significantly.. averaged probably 1 click per fight.<br>
<br>
Wiz + Wiz + Enc + Mag + Cler + Bard chardok AE group.  <br>
<br>
Wiz + Mag chilling out killing mobs in the upper chardok tunnel. (Wiz did most of the nuking and pulling.  I made rods and nuked a bit.. pet was also the tank)<br>
<br>
Warrior + Cleric + Druid + Enchanter + Magician + Shadowknight in the hole = Solid crawling group, enchanter didn't really like mezzing and played with charm instead.  I had enough mana to nuke freely.  I wasn't able to make full use of my right click nuke but felt that I was pulling my weight quite well anyway with nukes.<br>
<br>
Magician + Druid vs. Efreeti Lord Djarn = fun, didn't even notice that I got a nice chunk of xp.  Wizard would have been a great 3rd member.. though it probably would have made the crawl trivially easy.<br>
<br>
Bard(53 dinged 54) + Druid(60) + Magician( + c3 in the grey = over 100 kills per hour and average mob lifespan was approx 15 seconds.  great xp, ding 59 <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Wizard here would have done nothing but increased kill rate.  In fact, a wizard would probably be the absolute best choice of a fourth class in this situation.<br>
<br>
Exact same grey group plus a Shaman in kael, we crawled from bank to arena and managed to take out some of the outer arena mobs such as Trooper coldstone.  Mobs took minutes to kill, xp was slow and we didn't get lucky with loot, but the fights were really fun and xp was noticeable.  Downtime was fairly large but unavoidable for the group we had, a wizard would have fit in very well and would have had plenty of mana to make our battles much easier.<br>
<br>
Mage + warrior + cleric + monk + shaman + druid in Cazic Thule.  Long fights, no clarity = not very nuker friendly.  Not pet friendly either, and if I hadn't had a right click nuke I would have felt very weak.<br>
<br>
Mage + Cleric + Warrior + Druid in Umbral plains.  Long, long fights, no clarity... low downtime  /hug pet, DS, right click nukes.  Not very nuker friendly situation, though resists were not a big problem at all.  Added another cleric later on(played the role of extra nuker... wizard would have been superior).  Finally added a rogue who made a pretty noticeable difference.<br>
<br>
And that's pretty much it.  Nope, didn't waste any of my time getting killed by random pickup groups in seb or getting into silly fights about spawns at the frenzy in Velketors.  The kind of groups that think there is a &quot;normal&quot; way to do things and that 99% of the game is the same.<br>
<br>
Casters need tuning in some areas.  But lets not overstate the case by trying to oversimplify what it means to be a normal group.  Maybe I'm reading you wrong, but it seems to me that you guys would take that list I just gave and pick out all the most nuker unfriendly scenarios to call 'normal.'...  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uznailvh.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Znail vh</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/21/02 4:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> Goladus, it is not that hard to define a normal group. It is not about who are in the group, but what tactics are used. A normal group concentrate on killing one mob at a time with someone to tank. Thats it, its not harder then that. All but one, the AE group, of the groups you was in fall inside that deffinition. <br>
