OK aside from a clear attempt at setting yourself up as superior to the plebes who play the game other than you, you're missing the point totally.  A normal group is one that isn't on raids and isn't using AE.  It really is that simple, a group that goes somewhere, kills things one at a time, and gets experience (and perhaps some items).  The composition has nothing to do with this, its a NORMAL Everquest group.  You really are trying to complicate something I'm pretty sure you already understand clearly and simply. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 1853<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/21/02 10:32 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Goladus, it is not that hard to define a normal group. It is not about who are in the group, but what tactics are used. A normal group concentrate on killing one mob at a time with someone to tank. Thats it, its not harder then that. All but one, the AE group, of the groups you was in fall outside that deffinition. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, the tactics used each time were different.  And again...  killing one mob at a time with someone tanking is only one part of the strategy..  In some cases, a nuker fits in fine, in others they struggle.  Another point, is that crowd control was not always available..  we had two pulls a couple of times in the umbral group, and a careful wizard would have been able to make great use of Pillar spells, as in order to prevent the healer from getting aggro the warrior had to continually taunt both mobs.  Additionally, hard nuking on one target will serve as rudimentary crowd control and save healer mana.<br>
<br>
Choosing between small pulls and trains is only one strategic decision.  When determining the usefulness of a wizard, the fact that you will be getting single pulls is not the only important thing.<br>
<br>
Other important things:<br>
<br>
Mob hitpoints  (CT vs Grey)<br>
<br>
Mob resistances or immunities  (Dark assassins in umbral have snare immunity, Giants in Kael untunnable.. hole mobs have fairly high nuke resists, Grey mobs resist like.. never)<br>
<br>
Mob damage output  (Grey.. high  Chardok .. average)<br>
<br>
Mob special abilities (Like charm/gfux in sirens,  lifetaps, AE slow, rains, and so on in CT, enragers in Umbral..)<br>
<br>
Mob aggro tendancies (Grey mobs dumb as bricks.. Kael giants a bit more clever)<br>
<br>
Mob AC  (Umbral vs. Kael)<br>
<br>
Crowd control available  (Umbral vs. Grey)<br>
<br>
How much mana regen available?  (Note the grey group had bard song and c3 and potg, while the umbral group had no song and no clarity.. just potg)<br>
<br>
Snare available? (Yes in most cases..)<br>
<br>
Fear kite viable? (Not used)<br>
<br>
Safe camp available?  .. or is a crawl necessary?  (Umbral group had to move several times..  Grey group found an empty spot and pulled continuously)<br>
<br>
Evac available/needed?  Exodus saved CT group's asses.  Needed to get out of the hole..<br>
<br>
Coth available/needed?  Used in CT to get group past some mobs that we didn't want to fight.<br>
<br>
Slow available?  (CT yes, Umbral no)<br>
<br>
Haste available?  (Hole yes, Umbral no)<br>
<br>
Focus items?  (Um yes in all cases hehe... but for a wizard this would be a factor)<br>
<br>
AC of main tank?  (Umbral = awesome, Grey = medium(53 bard tank), Efreeti = ass(pet))<br>
<br>
levels of all members (Don't remember really.. lots of 60s, but of course there are 59 levels before 60 right grim?  Until recently most of my groups have been made up of various levelled people)<br>
<br>
Intensity of group...  (Some groups are just out to have some fun, and aren't going to be chain-pulling endlessly..  Grey vs. Efreeti..  In my experience, the most intense &quot;trinity&quot; groups are no more common than intense AE groups)<br>
<br>
ability to communicate<br>
Someone capable of single pulls?<br>
Chance of mid fight adds?<br>
Mobs undead?<br>
Summoned?<br>
Mobs never run away?<br>
Mobs damage shielded?<br>
<br>
.. you get the picture I hope..  there are just too many factors important to a damage caster to use only the term 'normal' groups to describe your balancing target.<br>
<br>
Differences in strategy do not have to be as drastic as AE group vs. Single pull group.  As was commonly argued, AE groups should not be the basis for wizard balancing, despite their increasing popularity and viability.  Besides...  I only listed one AE group, and there are many different ways to get an AE group to work.. depite the talk of wizards here that ONLY want to be in the most optimal, exploit level AE groups. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 1854<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/21/02 10:55 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> ok...<br>
