<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
 Its not &quot;specific&quot; situations that are particularly relevant to the LFG problem, its the way &quot;most&quot; groups do things. That baseline is what one will encounter 19 out of 20 times which means Mr. Wizard is going to generally have a bitch of a time finding a pick-up group. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I mean..  perhaps Torcer is right and there is really some standard thing that wizards will encounter 19 out of 20 times in a pickup group, but if there is I really couldn't explain it from my experience.<br>
<br>
I mean.. what happens when a member of this standard group leaves?  Does it now become a &quot;specific&quot; situation not relevant for balance discussion?  What if most of the time is actually spent in these &quot;specific&quot; situations and only rarely in the supposed normal group setting?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Something else to think about is that in none of the groups so would a wizard have done better then you as a magician. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Good point..<br>
<br>
However, in the grey group the pet was not the tank, the bard was.  Even a bard has much better AC than a mage pet, and it saved us a noticeable amount of mana.  I think that a wizard in my situation would have easily been as powerful as myself.  I forget the numbers but this was a session I did log, and I nuked for easily 2x the damage of the epic pet, probably more.  There were a couple of times that my pet did tank while the bard used charm, but I can't really speculate about what a wizard might have done in my place.<br>
<br>
The other groups with a pet tank was the Efreeti and the chardok tunnel.  /shrug I'm told that a level 60 epic wizard with decent equiment can solo Efreeti.  A magician cannot.. runners would kill me.<br>
<br>
In those situations where we had extreme amounts of uptime with low mana regen then yes, I was probably more valuable than a wizard.  Umbral comes to mind..  However, add in a conflag or rend robe and the wizards contribution will be much more respectable.<br>
<br>
The sirens group?  It's hard to say..  The Hole Group?  Also tough to say, probably the epic pet in both cases would set me apart from a wizard...  But to be honest I'm not an exactly fair comparison.  I know far more non-epic mages than epic mages.<br>
<br>
Also... who is to say that I should be the one replaced by a wizard?  In many cases the wizard could substitute for someone else.  For example, the second cleric in our umbral group would have been better off as a wizard, though an enchanter or shaman probably would have been more valuable.<br>
<br>
I'm fairly certian that a wizard would have outdone me in the Cazic Thule group.  My pet damage was absolutely pathetic.  The only things that was really keeping me going was damage shields(and the mobs spent most of the time slowed by a 60 shaman.. so DS damage wasn't even all <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> that</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> great) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uarmok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Armok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Need a log parsed?</span><br>  Posts: 855<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/21/02 12:35 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> I define a conventional group to be any group not focused on AE tactics. I define AE tactics to include PBAoE groups and any quadding (including team quadding). Basically, it's any group that focuses on single target tactics, including single kiting, fear kiting, and the more common pull singles/mez adds approach. Excluding raids is also reasonable, as the goals, tactics, and modes are different enough to warrant a separate analysis. In addition, most raids are multi-group endeavors, and thus falls out of the usual definition of &quot;group.&quot;<br>
<br>
For wizards, the formula is fairly simple: when mana expenditure exceeds mana regeneration, wizard performance starts to lag. Mana expenditure is a function of mana efficiency (dmg/mana) and uptime. Right click nukes also help with damage output, but the value of this is a function of average combat length, click activation time, and damage from the item. My charts show the relationships between these pretty well.<br>
<br>
But the bottom line is pretty much what you would expect: wizards in high uptime conventional groups (which comprise the vast majority of the game as experienced by the vast majority of player) lag and are in need of some balancing. <p>"Evacuate? In our moment of triumph? I think you overestimate their chances!"<BR>
Armok Komra (Triton)<BR>
Sorcerer Emeritus of Povar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/udoaal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>doaal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 176<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/28/02 1:20 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> I think casters need to be re-evaluated in a lot of ways.<br>
<br>
First I would increase casters hps slightly.  Its ridiculously low compared to melees (I know that casters should have the lowest hps of all classes and I don't want them to be tanks, but I still think it's way too low).<br>
<br>
Another problem is spell resistance.  Melees can have equal or greater spell resists with their gear (read: PERMANENT, not buffed) and have awesome AC.  Casters will never even come close to the AC a tank has.  I'm not saying that they should, just trying to show the unbalance here.  Melees can have awesome resists in both areas (spell and melee damage), whereas casters will only be awesome in one.  Not sure what a solution here would be, short of nerfing melee resists (which would probably make them mad).<br>
<br>
Some will argue that we have skin spells.  Sure it provides TEMPORARY defense, but doesn't increase our AC (which reduces the total damage you take) and sucks in a bit of damage.  This is only temporary however, unlike a melees gear which stays with him all the time (unless he dies).<br>
<br>
What I would suggest is removing the 66% damage cap for spell damage and adding a 66% cap to melee's resists for dueling only (so if they had 100FR it would be 66 in a duel situtation).  This way they won't get shafted for end-game encounters with AE, but will balance PvP somewhat I believe. Thoughts? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uaniar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aniar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 1007<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/28/02 1:47 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why do casters need balancing?</span><hr size=1> Caster balancing as doaal suggested would do absolutely nothing for PvE caster balance, which is what the first goal of the &quot;caster balance&quot; effort should be.  After PvE is fixed, THEN PvP can be looked at. <p><center>
